INSERT INTO `document_caches` VALUES (11079456, 'J Endocrinol Invest. 2000 Oct. 23(9):605-8', 'PD1 is a novel protein particularly expressed at the testicular level. The relative cDNA sequences were cloned from human and rat testis libraries revealing an open reading frame for a protein of 520 and 511 amino acids respectively. The human PD1 amino acid sequence shows 85% identity with rat sequence suggesting that PD1 gene has been highly conserved during mammalian evolution. Immunohistochemical analysis showed that this protein is detected in the tubular compartment of the testis and, in particular, in the cytoplasm of the Sertoli cells. PD1 expression is not constitutive but seems to be under the influence of neighboring spermatogenic cells as demonstrated by its reduction in hypospermatogenesis with respect to normal spermatogenesis and a further reduction in Sertoli cell-only syndrome. During testicular development in the rat (from 2 to 45 days of age) the PD1 mRNA level became detectable at 14 days and then increased steadily with an advancement of age. These findings suggest that PD1 may play a role in the regulation of spermatogenesis and may be a potential candidate gene for defects of male fertility.', NULL, '2000', 'A novel gene (PD1) with a potential role on rat spermatogenesis.', '2021-11-30 07:45:08', '2021-11-30 07:45:08', 'Onisto M, Graziotto R, Scannapieco P, Marin P, Merico M, Slongo ML, Foresta C', '<?xml version=\"1.0\" ?>\n<!DOCTYPE PubmedArticleSet PUBLIC \"-//NLM//DTD PubMedArticle, 1st January 2019//EN\" \"https://dtd.nlm.nih.gov/ncbi/pubmed/out/pubmed_190101.dtd\">\n<PubmedArticleSet><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"MEDLINE\" Owner=\"NLM\"><PMID Version=\"1\">11079456</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2001</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>22</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2018</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>13</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Print\">0391-4097</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Print\"><Volume>23</Volume><Issue>9</Issue><PubDate><Year>2000</Year><Month>Oct</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of endocrinological investigation</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Endocrinol Invest</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>A novel gene (PD1) with a potential role on rat spermatogenesis.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><MedlinePgn>605-8</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText>PD1 is a novel protein particularly expressed at the testicular level. The relative cDNA sequences were cloned from human and rat testis libraries revealing an open reading frame for a protein of 520 and 511 amino acids respectively. The human PD1 amino acid sequence shows 85% identity with rat sequence suggesting that PD1 gene has been highly conserved during mammalian evolution. Immunohistochemical analysis showed that this protein is detected in the tubular compartment of the testis and, in particular, in the cytoplasm of the Sertoli cells. PD1 expression is not constitutive but seems to be under the influence of neighboring spermatogenic cells as demonstrated by its reduction in hypospermatogenesis with respect to normal spermatogenesis and a further reduction in Sertoli cell-only syndrome. During testicular development in the rat (from 2 to 45 days of age) the PD1 mRNA level became detectable at 14 days and then increased steadily with an advancement of age. These findings suggest that PD1 may play a role in the regulation of spermatogenesis and may be a potential candidate gene for defects of male fertility.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Onisto</LastName><ForeName>M</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute of Histology and Embryology, University of Padova, Italy. onisto@civ.bio.unipd.it</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Graziotto</LastName><ForeName>R</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Scannapieco</LastName><Fore